# Fixture definition for the C oracle harness (tools/oracle/harness).
# See tools/oracle/gen-fixtures.sh for the format this file is parsed with:
# plain "key=value" lines, one per line, "#" starts a comment.
#
# dat        - .dat filename, resolved relative to tworld/data/
# level      - level index within the .dat file (0-based)
# ruleset    - "ms" or "lynx"
# rndseed    - seed passed to restartprng()
# rndslidedir- initial random-slide direction (0/1/2/4/8)
# stepping   - initial timer stepping offset (0-7)
# maxTicks   - number of ticks to simulate
# moves      - space-separated "when:dir" pairs (dir: 0=NIL 1=N 2=W 4=S 8=E)
#
# intro.dat level 2, "FRIENDS AND ENEMIES" under the MS ruleset -- exercises
# multiple monsters (bugs/gliders/etc) moving autonomously with no Chip
# input at all. MS's monster-stepping logic (mslogic.c) uses a different
# direction-preference/tie-break algorithm than Lynx's, so this is a good
# check that MS's internal creature list doesn't desync chipsneeded/
# statusflags/soundeffects even though it isn't exposed via the digest
# (see mslogic.c's module-static creature list, which has no accessor --
# hence "creatures":[] here, same as ms-intro-1).

dat=intro.dat
level=2
ruleset=ms
rndseed=1
rndslidedir=0
stepping=0
maxTicks=8
moves=
